<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n12005e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12005e">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12005e"> 5(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> credulous, helpful / always beaten</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> le d&eacute;mon, mis en sc&egrave;ne par nos paysans, est absolument le m&ecirc;me que le diable du Moyen-Age. Il en a tous les caract&egrave;res. Il est en g&eacute;n&eacute;ral cr&eacute;dule, assez serviable et complaisant <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> en d&eacute;finitive, il est sans cesse tromp&eacute;, bern&eacute;, dup&eacute; et roul&eacute; par la foi ou la malice des gens &agrave; qui il a affaire. <br><font color="green">[&hellip; the demon described by our peasants is absolutely the same as the devil of the Middle Ages. He has all the characteristics. He is generally credulous, somewhat helpful, and accommodating [&hellip;]</font> in short he is always beaten, fooled, duped, and thwarted by the faith or the cunning of the people he deals with with.] <small> l'Abb&eacute; A. Millon, <a name="AMPB" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#AMPB"><cite title="source">Pauvres Pierres! Les Megalithes Bretons devant la science</cite></a> (n.d) 15</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
